{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504122"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:11:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:11:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2301"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2301"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.62,0.06,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2301"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86143"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36745"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man diagnosed with Parkinson\u2019s disease presents to his general practitioner with difficulty walking. He was diagnosed two years ago. Over the past few months, his family reports that he has episodes of \u0022freezing up\u0022 and difficulty initiating movement. They also worry that his limb movements are getting slower. His family bought him a single-point walking cane but he has fallen several times when using this. He attributes this due to his unsteady balance. He has no other significant medical co-morbidities. He takes regular levodopa with no complains or side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he presents with a shuffling gait and stooped posture. He appears unsteady as he walks with his single-point walking cane across the room. There is evidence of freezing of gait.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best mobility aid for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Switch to a two-wheel walker","Switch to a four-wheel walker","Switch to a standard walker","Switch to a wheelchair","Continue using the single-point walking cane"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe severity of Parkinson disease determines the type of walking aid a patient will require. However, we note this question and associated feedback is general; mobility aid prescription should be guided by the patient\u0027s individual pathology and deficits, as well as their preferences. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Emild\u003C/strong\u003E cases of Parkinson\u0027s disease, a \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle-point walking cane can be utilised\u003C/strong\u003E. This helps the patient to balance whilst providing minimal weight-bearing support. It is often indicated in patients with solely balance problems or moderate unilateral joint pain. However, this patient\u0027s Parkinson\u0027s disease is progressively worsening and he requires further aid with his balance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe best mobility aid for a progressively worsening Parkinson\u2019s disease is a \u003Cstrong\u003E4-wheel walker. \u003C/strong\u003EA walker with four wheels on each leg does not have to be lifted. The patient is forced to push the walker while in forward flexion which prevents retropulsion. This prevents patients with unsteady gait from falling backwards. A 4-wheel walker provides the most improved safety and speed with the least variability and impact on the individual\u0027s ability to walk at their usual speed. There are hand brakes on 4-wheel walker that can be used if there was propulsion and this would prevent him falling forward.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etwo-wheel walker \u003C/strong\u003Emay also be utilised, however, this impairs the patient\u0027s gait speed and is associated with freezing episodes. Two-wheel walkers tend to have a large turning radius - because of this, people will often pick up the walker to turn which can lead to a fall. Furthermore, the need to multi-task (walking and lifting the walker simultaneously) may increase the risk of bradykinesia and freezing of gait.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Estandard walker\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by its use of platforms at the bottom of each leg, rather than wheels. It is contraindicated in Parkinson\u0027s disease as it may cause retropulsion and may lead to falls. It is indicated in patients with bilateral lower-extremity weakness and requires good upper-extremity strength. However, it also increases energy expenditure and slows the patient down.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ewheelchair\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this case. If the patient is able, the four-wheel walker should be used first before recommending the use of wheelchair.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing using the single-point walking cane\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as he is already having falls; thus, a more stable form of aid is required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A standard walker in a patient with Parkinson\u2019s disease may lead to retropulsion and falls.","General, a 4-wheel walker is the best mobility aid for progressive Parkinson\u0027s disease."],"references":["Kegelmeyer DA, Parthasarathy S, Kostyk SK, White SE, Kloos AD. Assistive devices alter gait patterns in Parkinson disease: advantages of the four-wheeled walker. Gait Posture. 2013;38(1):20-4. doi: 10.1016/j.gaitpost.2012.10.027","Charette C, Best KL, Smith EM, et al. Walking Aid Use in Canada: Prevalence and Demographic Characteristics Among Community-Dwelling Users. Phys Ther 2018; 98:571.","Mahoney J, Euhardy R, Carnes M. A comparison of a two-wheeled walker and a three-wheeled walker in a geriatric population. J Am Geriatr Soc 1992; 40:208.","Holder CG, Haskvitz EM, Weltman A. The effects of assistive devices on the oxygen cost, cardiovascular stress, and perception of nonweight-bearing ambulation. J Orthop Sports Phys Ther 1993; 18:537.","Kegelmeyer DA, parthasarathy S, Kostyk SK, et al. Assistive devices alter gait patterns in Parkinson disease: advantages of the four-wheeled walker. Gait Posture. 2013; 38 (1): 20-24","Frontera, Walter R., and Joel A DeLisa. Physical Medicine \u0026 Rehabilitation: Principles and Practice. 6th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins Health, 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2301"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86143"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T21:59:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T22:00:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2301"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi